iUnderstanding Open5GS Components		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iOpen5GS, as its name suggests, is primarily a software that implements		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ia 5G core network (as well as a LTE core network). Since the core		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
inetwork protocols and structure in the 5G era are significantly		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
idifferent from the 4G era, especially for standalone 5G SA networks,		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iOpen5GS can roughly be seen as a set of LTE/5G NSA core network		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
isoftware, plus a set of 5G SA core network software, with a small		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iportion of components shared between them.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iThe LTE/5G NSA part of Open5GS consists of the following components:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- MME - Mobility Management Entity		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- HSS - Home Subscriber Server		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- PCRF - Policy and Charging Rules Function		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- SGWC - Serving Gateway Control Plane		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- SGWU - Serving Gateway User Plane		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- SMF - Session Management Function		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- SMF itself is a 5G core network component, but Open5GS SMF also		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iimplements the Packet Gateway Control Plane in the 4G core network		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
istructure.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- UPF - User Plane Function		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- UPF itself is a 5G core network component, but Open5GS UPF also		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iimplements the Packet Gateway User Plane in the 4G core network		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
istructure.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- SCP -		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iSecure, Contain, Protect		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iService Communication Proxy		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- SCP itself is a 5G core network component, but SMF depends on it.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- NRF - NF Repository Function		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- NRF itself is a 5G core network component, but SCP depends on it.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iAnd the 5G SA part consists of the following components:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- NRF - NF Repository Function		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- SCP - Service Communication Proxy		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- SEPP - Security Edge Protection Proxy		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- AMF - Access and Mobility Management Function		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- SMF - Session Management Function		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- UPF - User Plane Function		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- AUSF - Authentication Server Function		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- UDM - Unified Data Management		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- UDR - Unified Data Repository		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- PCF - Policy and Charging Function		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- NSSF - Network Slice Selection Function		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- BSF - Binding Support Function		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iThese components communicate with each other in the following		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
istructure:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
IOpen5GS Component Architecture Diagram	/usr/uploads/202507/Open5GS_CUPS-01.jpg	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i(Image source:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
hOpen5GS official documentation	URL:https://open5gs.org/open5gs/docs/guide/01-quickstart/	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iThe communication between various components of the 4G/5G core network		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iuses the standardized		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
hDiameter protocol	URL:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diameter_(protocol)	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i, which is based on TCP or		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
hSCTP	URL:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stream_Control_Transmission_Protocol	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iprotocol, exchanging data between various components of the 4G/5G core		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
inetwork. This also means that hardware and software from different		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ivendors, as long as they support the Diameter protocol, can join the		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
isame core network and jointly provide services to mobile users.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iHowever, in this post, I will only use Open5GS components, and will		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
inot add other components to the core network for now.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iInstalling Open5GS Package		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iIf you are using Ubuntu, you can refer to the		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
hOpen5GS official installation tutorial	URL:https://open5gs.org/open5gs/docs/guide/01-quickstart/	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iDuring this process, in addition to installing the Open5GS binaries, a		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iset of systemd services corresponding to each Open5GS component is		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
icreated, and the default Open5GS configuration is copied to `/etc`.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iSince NixOS only has the Open5GS package (`pkgs.open5gs`) and no		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
icorresponding NixOS module, we need to manually create systemd		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iservices for Open5GS, mimicking the installation process on other		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
isystems like Ubuntu:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iCreating Open5GS Configuration Files		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iIf you are using Ubuntu, the above installation process should have		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iautomatically installed the default configuration files to		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i`/etc/freeDiameter` and `/etc/open5gs`. However, in NixOS, this		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iprocess is not automatic, and we need to manually copy the		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iconfiguration files or manually specify their paths.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iSince the Nixpkgs Open5GS package already comes with a set of default		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iconfigurations, we can directly copy the default configuration files		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ifrom this package. First, build the package:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iIf all goes well, Nix will download the pre-compiled Open5GS from the		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iBinary Cache and symlink it to the `result` directory. At this point,		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iwe can see the default configuration files in the `result/etc` folder:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iThen we can copy them to our NixOS configuration for later		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
imodification:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iFor files in the `freeDiameter` folder, we need to place them under		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i`/etc/freeDiameter`:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iFor files in the `open5gs` folder, you can directly specify the		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iconfiguration file path using the `-c` parameter when starting		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iOpen5GS:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iNot placing them in `/etc` ensures that Open5GS services will		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iautomatically restart after modifying the configuration files.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iFixing Paths in Open5GS Configuration Files under NixOS		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iSince Open5GS packaged in Nixpkgs is installed by default under a path		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iin `/nix/store`, its configuration files also references many paths		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iunder `/nix/store` by default.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iFirst, get the actual installation path of Open5GS:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iThen search for this path in the copied configuration files. You will		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
isee many places containing the full path:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iOnce the Open5GS package or its dependencies are updated, the path of		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iOpen5GS in the Nix store will change, causing files specified by		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iabsolute paths to become invalid, and preventing Open5GS from		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
istarting. Therefore, we need to keep these paths synchronized with the		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iOpen5GS path, or point them outside the Nix store, to prevent future		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iissues.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iMy workaround is to first link a copy of the `pkgs.open5gs` package to		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i`/etc`:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iThen modify the above paths:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iAfter the modification, we will be able to upgrade Open5GS without		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iissues in the future, and our configuration files placed in `/etc`		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iwill take effect normally.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i(Optional) Regenerate Diameter TLS Certificates		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iOpen5GS packaged in Nixpkgs comes with a TLS certificate generated		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iduring the build process. If your Open5GS is downloaded from the		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iBinary Cache instead of being compiled locally, you will be using the		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
isame TLS key  others can download from the Binary Cache.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iIf you deploy on a single machine according to this tutorial, since		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iall communication is local and does not go through external networks,		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iencryption and private key leakage have little impact on security.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iHowever, if you plan to place some components on other machines, or if		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iyou do not want to use this leaked key, you can generate a new one		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iusing the following script:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iWhen you run `systemctl start open5gs-certs.service`, this service		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iwill automatically generate missing keys in `/var/lib/open5gs-certs`.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iThen you can modify the Open5GS configuration file to point the TLS		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ikey path to `/var/lib/open5gs-certs`:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iYou can also add `open5gs-certs.service` to the `After` and `Requires`		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iof each Open5GS systemd service to ensure that the keys are generated		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ibefore Open5GS starts.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
