iSummary		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iThis post mainly records the steps that differ from the Magma core		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
inetwork when setting up Open5GS, as well as some issues specific to		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
isetting it up on NixOS. Compared to Magma, Open5GS has a simpler		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iinstallation process and does not rely on containerization management		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
itools like Docker. If you are using Ubuntu, most of the above process		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iis actually automatically completed during `apt install`.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iFrom the perspective of LTE terminal devices (e.g., mobile phones),		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ithere is no difference in using these two core network software. Both		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ihave similar latency and network bandwidth, mainly limited by LTE		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
icommunication itself. (Except for the strange bug I encountered with		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iMagma where Android phones could not authenticate properly.)		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iI switched to Open5GS for the management convenience mentioned at the		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ibeginning. You can choose either Open5GS or Magma based on your		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ipreference.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}